iret, Manche, and Marne called Courcy.","History: Nicolas Lemière <i>dit</i> Courcy from Courcy in Manche, France, married Louise-Geneviève Dubé in Rivière-Ouelle, QC, in 1749."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Guillaume","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>William</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Guillaume de Courcy I was born in 1136 as the son of Raoul de Courcy. He married N de Tancarville. He died in 1176, at the age of 40."},"et":{"1136–1176":"1136–1176","1140–1187":"1140–1187","1168–1213":"1168–1213","1167–Female":"1167–Surnud","1108–1167":"1108–1167","1136":"1136","1213":"1213","1168":"1168","1167":"1167","1176":"1176","1187":"1187","about 1168":"umbes 1168","1140":"1140","1108":"1108","Islip, Oxfordshire, England":"Islip, Oxfordshire, England"},"fi":{"1136–1176":"1136–1176","1140–1187":"1140–1187","1168–1213":"1168–1213","1167–Female":"1167–Kuollut","1108–1167":"1108–1167","1136":"1136","1213":"1213","1168":"1168","1167":"1167","1176":"1176","1187":"1187","about 1168":"noin 1168","1140":"1140","1108":"1108","Islip, Oxfordshire, England":"Islip, Oxfordshire, England"},"fr":{"1136–1176":"1136–1176","1140–1187":"1140–1187","1168–1213":"1168–1213","1167–Female":"1167–Décédée","1108–1167":"1108–1167","1136":"1136","1213":"1213